# The equality pulse

In 2025 the world emitted close to 45 Tons of CO2. Although this is the largest annual tonnage in human history there are many reasons to expect this number to go down soon, perhaps all the way to zero. Nate Hagens refers to this surge of fossil fuel usage as the “carbon pulse”. However the latter half of this mobilization of force was accompanied by another pulse that is rarely described as such.

[![][image1]](http://global_co2.png)

The foundations of the equality pulse can be found in the beginning of the 20th century. conditions conspired to bring about a great demand for autonomous highly educated individuals. Warfare, logistics and energy production were all bounded by the ability of economies to mobilize highly skilled individuals to organize them. For a time it was impossible to win a global war or run a cold war economy without the employment of a vast spreadsheet class of employees. An army of people that were able to consistently turn pen and paper into mobilization that 

**Image rising democracy**  
[**https://www.researchgate.net/publication/351635550\_Waves\_of\_autocratization\_and\_democratization\_a\_rejoinder**](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/351635550_Waves_of_autocratization_and_democratization_a_rejoinder)

In term these people extracted far more political and economic equality from their societies. Between 1900 and 2000 the richest 10% of developed economies transferred more than half of their wealth and income to a section of society now named the middle class. Freed from living from paycheck to paycheck they organized and forced political concessions such as universal suffrage, pensions and labor protections.

**Pikety equality since 1800**

Since 2000 this development has begun to reverse. As various types of computer technology reduced demand organizing labor these bargaining powers have started to evaporate. All across the world democracy and freedom of speech is in retreat. Wealth and income distributions are converging back to the shape they held in Victorian times.

[**![][image2]**](http://inheritance.png)

Some people such as Thomas Piketty argue that this reduction in political and economic equality is temporary and that the long term march is towards greater equality not smaller. They are sorely mistaken. The long term trend is towards ever more concentrated control over the world in an ever smaller space. In prokaryotic colony life every cell could reproduce. Early multicellular life distributed control throughout its body but within cells control was now executed from a cellular nucleus. With every successive processing innovation an ever greater mass is motivated by a relatively ever smaller volume of cells.

**Centralization over time.**

With the arrival of human sapience this evolution went across individuals. First organized themselves in tribes, then in cities, then in nations and now in globe spanning supra national organizations and corporations. Each one with a singular individual, while not quite in full control but certainly in a leadership position. Now a single orange haired man in a poorly fitting business suit can with the push of a button mobilize the power of the sun to wipe all higher organisms from the face of the world.

Funny enough the aspects of the current system that make an more centralized one more   
If we were more centrally organized and of unified will we could stop the processes that are about to take away the life we so cherish. We could understand what was happening, and take action to stop it. Unfortunately both the path we are on and the actions to correct it are heavily contested. Whatever comes after the equality pulse, it is unlikely to include a middle class, if you are in the middle class enjoy it while it lasts.
